Chapter 0.2 – What Actually Happens When You Click Run?

This is one of the most important concepts in programming.

Most beginners think:

"I wrote Python code. I clicked Run. It worked."

An engineer asks:

"What happened inside the computer?"

Today, we'll answer that question.

Our Journey

When you click Run in VS Code, your code goes through several stages:

You
   │
   ▼
Python Code
   │
   ▼
Python Interpreter
   │
   ▼
Operating System
   │
   ▼
CPU
   │
   ▼
Memory (RAM)
   │
   ▼
Output on Screen

Let's understand each part.

Step 1 — You Write Code

Example:

print("Hello, Dev!")

This is called source code.

It's written for humans to read.

The CPU cannot understand this directly.

Step 2 — VS Code Does NOT Run Your Code

Many people think VS Code executes Python.

It doesn't.

VS Code is just a code editor.

Think of it like Microsoft Word.

It helps you:

write code
edit code
organize projects

But it does not execute Python code by itself.

Step 3 — VS Code Calls the Python Interpreter

When you press:

▶ Run

VS Code actually runs something similar to:

python main.py

Now the real work begins.

What is the Python Interpreter?

The Python interpreter is a software program whose job is to:

read Python code
understand it
execute it

Imagine a translator.

You speak English.

The CPU only understands machine instructions.

The interpreter translates your Python program into operations the computer can execute.

Step 4 — The Interpreter Reads Your Code

Suppose you wrote:

print("Hello")

The interpreter reads:

print

It recognizes:

"This is the built-in function that displays text."

Then it reads:

"Hello"

It prepares that text for output.

Step 5 — Memory (RAM)

Everything your program needs is stored temporarily in RAM.

Example:

name = "Dev"

RAM now contains:

name
↓

"Dev"

Variables live in memory while the program runs.

Step 6 — CPU Executes Instructions

The CPU is the computer's processor.

It performs operations like:

calculations
comparisons
moving data
displaying output

The CPU never reads Python directly.

It executes lower-level instructions generated as the interpreter processes your code.

Step 7 — The Operating System Helps

The operating system (Windows, Linux, macOS) acts as the manager between your program and the hardware.

When your program wants to:

print text
open a file
use the internet
allocate memory

it requests these services through the operating system.

Step 8 — Output Appears

Finally,

print("Hello")

becomes

Hello

displayed on your screen.

Complete Flow


You write code

↓

VS Code

↓

Python Interpreter

↓

Operating System

↓

CPU + RAM

↓

Screen Output


Real-Life Analogy

Imagine a restaurant.

You → Customer

Python Code → Your food order

Python Interpreter → Waiter

Operating System → Restaurant manager

CPU → Chef

RAM → Kitchen workspace

Output → Your meal

The waiter (interpreter) translates your request into actions the chef can perform, while the manager coordinates resources.

Engineering Insight

The CPU doesn't know what print() means.

It only knows simple machine-level operations.

The Python interpreter bridges the gap between your human-readable code and the CPU's executable instructions.

Common Beginner Misconceptions

❌ "VS Code runs Python."

✅ VS Code launches the Python interpreter.

❌ "Python code goes directly into the CPU."

✅ The interpreter processes Python code before the CPU executes the resulting operations.

❌ "Variables are stored inside Python."

✅ Variable values are stored in your computer's memory (RAM) while the program runs.

Key TakeawaysR:

VS Code is an editor, not the Python runtime.
The Python interpreter executes Python programs.
The operating system provides services like memory management and screen output.
The CPU performs the actual computations.
RAM temporarily stores your program's data.
Every program follows a chain from source code to execution.
